  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Level Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Impose penalties and fines for non-compliance\n\n3. Criminal Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity\n\n4. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Reserve\n\n5. State Level:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes by establishing comprehensive legal frameworks for combating money laundering.",
